    "created_at": "2012-09-07T16:10:31Z",
    "updated_at": "2012-09-07T16:12:26Z",
    "body": "If we have one string type, it's going to need to be automatically reclaimed somehow (by global GC or by atomic reference counting). Both of these have huge performance costs. Atomic reference counting is _not_ going to be more efficient than what we have now.\n\nIn Rust, managed memory is always opt-in. Rust programmers should be free to control the lifetimes of their strings explicitly (through unique pointers and borrowing).\n",
    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
